                \n {"practice":"1","code":"SM-12","subCode":"undefined","explanation":"Process verification ensures that all security-related processes are completed and documented before product release, aligning with IEC 62443-4-1 requirements.","context":"Critical for ICS environments where security gaps can lead to operational disruptions or safety incidents. Ensures traceability and compliance.","challenges":["Lack of standardized documentation formats can lead to inconsistencies. Example: Different teams using varied templates for process records.","Ensuring all processes are covered, especially in complex ICS products. Example: Missing a firmware update verification step in a PLC release.","Maintaining up-to-date records as processes evolve. Example: Failing to document changes in patch management procedures.","Integrating verification with existing development workflows. Example: Security checks delaying agile release cycles.","Auditing verification processes for compliance. Example: External auditors finding gaps in documented evidence."],"best_practices":[{"description":"Use automated tools to track process completion. Example: Integrating JIRA with Confluence for real-time documentation. Link: Siemens ICS Security Guide.","url":" https://new.siemens.com/global/en/products/automation/industry-software/automation-software/tia-portal.html","url_description":"Siemens' guide on integrating security processes in ICS development."},{"description":"Define clear roles for verification tasks. Example: Assigning a security lead to sign off on each process. Link: Rockwell Automation Whitepaper.","url":"https://www.rockwellautomation.com/en-us/resources/white-papers.html","url_description":"Rockwell's approach to role-based security verification."},{"description":"Conduct pre-release audits. Example: Third-party review of patch management records. Link: Honeywell ICS Security Case Study.","url":"https://www.honeywellprocess.com/library/support/Pages/security.aspx","ur